Q: Qt demo?
qtdemo-qt4
C++ code: /usr/lib64/qt4/examples


Q: Compiled?
So, Qt apps are compiled in a 3 steps operations
A .pro file is written to describe the project to compile
A makefile is generated using qmake
The program is build using make (or nmake or jom on windows)

Q: Sample qmake command?
/usr/bin/qmake-qt4 -spec /usr/lib64/qt4/mkspecs/linux-g++-64 -o Makefile ../01_hello_world_button/01_hello_world_button.pro

Q: what is moc?
metaobject compiler.

#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
# MACROS

Q: The most important macro?
The most important macro is Q_OBJECT. 
Signal – Slot connections and their syntax cannot be intepreted by regular C++ compiler. 
The moc is provided to translate the QT syntax like “connect”, “signals”, “slots”, etc into regular C++ syntax. 
This is done by specifying the Q_OBJECT macro in the header containing class definitions that use such syntax.

mywidget.h
class MyWidget : public QWidget
{
    Q_OBJECT
public:
    MyWidget(QWidget *parent = 0);
...
}

Q: Others marker macros for moc? 
* signals
* public / protected / private slots
that mark the different methods that need to be extended.
example:
#ifndef WINDOW_H
#define WINDOW_H
 
#include <QWidget>
 
class QPushButton;
class Window : public QWidget
{
    Q_OBJECT
public:
    explicit Window(QWidget *parent = 0);
private slots:
    void slotButtonClicked(bool checked);
private:
    QPushButton *m_button;                          // m_ means member of the class!
};
 
#endif // WINDOW_H

Q: Reference vs pointer?

class MyClass :  public QOBject
{
    Q_OBJECT
public:
    MyClass(const QString &text, QObject *parent = 0 );     // <-- Passage by reference vs pointer?
    const QString& text() const;
    int getLengthOfText() const;
public slots:
    void setText(const QString &text);
signals:
    void textChanged(const QString &);
private:
    QString m_text;
};

void MyClass::setText( const QString &text)
{
    if (m_text == text) 
        return;
    m_text = text;                                          // <-- equality between strings ok in C++ !
    emit textChanged(m_text);
}; 
